    "In particular, we have definedK[f](t, w) = ∫ R×I ( Bω p + ε)G(w, v)(w -v)f (t, B, v)dBdv, J [f ℓ](w) = ∫ I G(w, z)(w -z)f ℓ (z)dz.As already mentioned, we also have to complete the Fokker-Planck equation (13) with no-flux boundary conditions for any t ≥ 0, specifically⎧ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎨ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎪ ⎩ D 2 (w)f (t, A, w)| w=±1 = 0 ∀A ∈ R, ( Āω p + ε)λ p K[f](t, w)f (t, A, w) + σ 2 p 2 ∂ w (D 2 (w)f (t, A, w))| w=±1 = 0 ∀A ∈ R, ( Āω ℓ + ε)λ ℓ J [f ℓ](w)f (t, A, w) + σ 2 ℓ 2 ∂ w (D 2 (w)f (t, A, w))| w=±1 = 0 ∀A ∈ R, lim A→±∞ A κ f (t, A, w) = 0 ∀w ∈ I,(16)where κ ≥ 1, and the last condition ensures that the first κ-th moments in A of f (t, A, w) are finite.",
    "We will prove (see Proposition 3) that, if the initial distribution has a compact support (as one would expect), then the support of f (t, A, w) remains bounded for any time t > 0, hence the last condition of ( 16) is not restrictive.",
    "Note that the first condition of ( 16) is related to the property D(±1) = 0.",
    "Finally, notice that the parameters λ p and λ ℓ, measuring the agents' disposition to compromise, appear in the drift terms of ( 14) and (15), while the parameters σ 2 p and σ 2 ℓ, measuring the agents' propensity to self-thinking, appear as coefficients in the diffusion operators.",
    "Consequently, small values of ν p = σ 2 p /λ p and ν ℓ = σ 2 ℓ /λ ℓ correspond to compromise-dominated opinion dynamics, while large values of these ratios denote self-thinking-dominated opinion dynamics.2.2."
